<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1904-11-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1904-11-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="159" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d159">
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                    <persName type="to">Conger</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1904-11-23"><hi rend="italic">November 23,
                                    1904</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                        <p>(Mr. Hay states that the views of this Government on the payment of the
                            Chinese indemnity in silver were stated in Department’s telegram of July
                            11, 1902 (printed below). In accepting the decision reached by the
                            Chinese Government the United States Government expects the same
                            treatment as the other interested powers.</p>
                        <pb facs="0272" n="184" xml:id="pg_184"/>
                        <frus:attachment>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Inclosure.]</seg></opener>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hay</persName> to Mr.
                                        <persName type="to">Conger</persName></hi>.</head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1902-07-11"><hi rend="italic">July 11,
                                        1902</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Our position, payment indemnity in silver, is not attempted new
                                interpretation of terms protocol; but the United States Government
                                has always understood this to be meaning of agreement. The President
                                reserves full liberty of action whatever may be decision
                                reached.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">John Hay.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </frus:attachment>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>